post_text: In addition to SACS/CASI accreditation through AdvancEd, all five schools and the school system are “Accredited with Quality” by the Georgia Accrediting Commission (GAC). This accrediting process, completed annually, ensures that schools and school districts provide quality, safe facilities and offer a viable, appropriate instructional program for all students. Congratulations to all of our schools for earning this distinction!

We are proud to recognize 7 of our Family Career and Community Leaders of America students that qualified for FCCLA National Conference for their competitive events. The students would have attended this conference in Washington, DC but due to COVID-19, the conference was held virtually. Each of these students were responsible for recording their presentations and submitting an electronic version of their projects and portfolios. Their events were scored by judges across the nation and our FCHS students made Fannin County proud!

Career Investigation Level 3, Sydney Tarpley, 11th grade- Gold Medal

Chapter Service Project Portfolio Level 2, Anna Rhodes and Gracie Stewart, 9th grade- Gold Medal

Chapter Service Project Portfolio Level 3- Bailey Pettit, 10th grade and Alexis Hill, 11th grade- Gold Medal

Interpersonal Communications Level 3, Isabella Tocci, 11th grade- Silver Medal

Say Yes to FCS Level 3, Sierra Reynolds, 11th grade- Gold Medal

Check out this video made by Lauren Owenby, FCCLA Sponser, that highlights their accomplishments.

post_text:
During the Spring semester, the FCHS video students worked with the Fannin County Arts Association to produce a documentary about the economic evolution of Fannin County. The video was part of the Smithsonian Crossroads project, and the final product will be housed at the Smithsonian in Washington, DC. Mercier Orchards, The Copper Basin Mines, and Blue Ridge Scenic Railway formed the foundation of the video.

Bubba Gibbs supervised this project and he is very proud of the students that worked on the project through the difficult environment of school from home! A special recognition goes to Sophomore Alex Higgins for writing and recording all of the music for the video. We would also like to recognize 2020 FCHS Graduate Ryan Petersen for his exceptional job with the voice over.

Without the help and support of Nichole Potzauf with the Blue Ridge Mountain Arts Association and Steve Procko with Steve Procko Productions, this video would not have been possible.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cKVqpM6_jU4

Fannin County Middle School
July 30 at 11:56 PM ·

Important Open House Information:
As with most everything else, our open house will look a little different this year. Open House on Thursday, August 6th will be FOR UPCOMING 6th graders only. We will be doing guided tours at specific times. If your 6th grade student’s last name begins with the letters A through G, please arrive at 2:00 pm. If your 6th grade student’s last name begins with the letters H through O, please arrive at 3:00pm. And if your 6th grade student’s last name begins with P through Z, please arrive at 4:00pm. You will be given further guidance and specific tour information at that time. We will take small groups on brief tours. Don't worry, 7th and 8th graders: your homeroom teachers will be contacting you early in the week to let you know where to go on the first day. Thank you for your continued patience and understanding.

post_text:
Gov. Brian P. Kemp announced that the Georgia Broadband Deployment Initiative (GBDI) is launching the Speedtest by Ookla® pilot project statewide through August. This project is designed to equip school leaders with the clearest picture possible of internet connectivity for Georgia’s students and teachers for the upcoming school year.
Georgians are encouraged to download the free Ookla Speedtest app (Android or iOS-Apple) to the various devices that they use to connect to the internet (smartphones, tablets, laptops, and desktop computers) and take several tests in the places where connectivity is important to them. The easy-to-use Speedtest, along with the information available at the Broadband Initiative website, will assist school leaders as they plan for their digital learning strategies.

Gov. Brian P. Kemp announced that the Georgia Broadband Deployment Initiative (GBDI) is launching the Speedtest by Ookla® pilot project statewide through August. This project is designed to equip school leaders with the clearest picture possible of internet connectivity for Georgia’s students and teachers for the upcoming school year.
Georgians are encouraged to download the free Ookla Speedtest app (Android or iOS-Apple) to the various devices that they use to connect to the internet (smartphones, tablets, laptops, and desktop computers) and take several tests in the places where connectivity is important to them. The easy-to-use Speedtest, along with the information available at the Broadband Initiative website, will assist school leaders as they plan for their digital learning strategies.

This award of distinction is presented to organizations that submit quality financial statements and supporting documentation in a timely manner, whose annual financial report is given an unmodified audit opinion and is free from any significant deficiencies or material weaknesses, and comply with all Transparency in Government Act requirements. Director of Finance, Susan Wynn and her department are pictured with the Board.

FREE COVID-19 Testing at Pop-Up Sites in North Georgia Continues Next Week
NORTH GA – Now that many North Georgians have been tested through Pop-Up COVID-19 Testing sites by public health in Fannin, Pickens and Murray counties, even more opportunities for testing at these sites will be offered next week.

Public health COVID-19 testing is FREE; however, anyone wanting to be tested at these sites must first call to register and arrange an appointment at 1-888-881-1474.

The times and locations for the Pop-Up COVID-19 Testing sites next week are:

• Fannin County: Tuesday, May 19th, 9 A.M. – 12 P.M., Blue Ridge United Methodist Church, 235 Orvin Lance Drive, Blue Ridge, GA 30513

• Pickens County: Wednesday, May 20th, 9 A.M. – 12 P.M., Mt. Zion Baptist Church, 1036 North Main Street, Jasper, GA 30143

• Murray County: Thursday, May 21st, 9 A.M. – 12 P.M., Murray County Parks and Recreation Department, 651 Hyden Tyler Road, Chatsworth, GA 30705

Additional Pop-Up COVID-19 Testing Times in North Georgia

NORTH GA – Dozens of North Georgians have been tested so far at the public health Pop-Up COVID-19 Testing sites in Fannin, Pickens and Murray counties, and now those county health departments will provide additional times for testing next week.

COVID-19 testing conducted by public health is FREE. The days, times and locations for the upcoming Pop-Up COVID-19 Testing sites are:

• Fannin County: Tuesday, May 12th, 9 A.M. – 11 A.M., Blue Ridge United Methodist Church, 235 Orvin Lance Drive, Blue Ridge, GA 30513

• Pickens County: Wednesday, May 13th, 9 A.M. – 11 A.M., Mt. Zion Baptist Church, 1036 North Main Street, Jasper, GA 30143

• Murray County: Thursday, May 14th, 9 A.M. – 11 A.M., Murray County Parks and Recreation Department, 651 Hyden Tyler Road, Chatsworth, GA 30705

Anyone who wishes to be tested at the public health pop-up clinics must first register by calling 1-888-881-1474.
For more information visit: http://nghd.org/pr/34-/1178-additional-pop-up-covid-19-testing-times-in-north-georgia.html

shared_text:
The Rebellion-FCHS Drama Troupe 6952
April 7 at 11:04 PM ·

So, as many of you already know, we’ve had to cut our season so insanely short due to the COVID outbreak and many other legal issues that follow, such as licensing, rescheduling, and many other variables of which many are unaware. To say this virus took a lot from so many is an understatement. Our prayers go out to everyone affected by this horrible time in history!

We still wanted to thank you, the Fannin Community, for all of the support for our shows, this year, past, and future! Here is a small sampling of what could have been, karaoke style, of course! May you all remain safe and blessed!

School Closure/Meal Delivery Update:

Spring break begins this Friday, April 10. The Fannin County School System will continue to run bus routes through Thursday, April 9, and provide breakfast and lunch each day along the routes.

Breakfast and lunch meals will continue at the elementary schools through Thursday, April 9 from 11:00 a.m. to 1:00 p.m. Additional meals (for this weekend) will be available at the three elementary schools on Thursday, April 9.

Families in need of food during spring break may contact Fannin County Family Connection at 706-632-6063.

Fannin County School System will resume daily meal services on Monday, April 20.

post_text: Need some positive news? Check this out! #FanninFamily #TSA #FanninsFuture
shared_text:
Fannin County High School
April 2 at 4:44 PM ·

Fannin County High School student, Bryce Ware, is working to produce protective masks for medical workers in our area. Bryce is using the MakerBot 3D printers from the Engineering classroom at FCHS to 3D print respirator mask bases. It takes approximately 9 hours to produce one mask base. Bryce is working closely with Dr. Causey with Causey Orthodontics in Blairsville, GA. Dr. Causey is combining the 3D printed bases with filters and distributing them where needed.

Bryce is an active member of the Technology Student Association (TSA,) and we are very proud of him for using his talents to help with this noble cause.

Attached are some pictures of Bryce with the 3D printer, and here is a link to a video that he produced explaining what he is doing!

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZLiFTPNbULE

Great job Bryce!

Report cards/progress reports will be available on Parent Portal for students in grades 1-12 via the Grades or the Reports Tabs tomorrow.

All students in grades 6-12 have a Student Portal account and may access the grades just like parents can in Parent Portal.

Parent/Guardians that do not have an existing Portal account may request one by emailing technologyhub@fannin.k12.ga.us. Please provide your name and your students name/s.

PLEASE NOTE!!!!! Only a parent or guardian can request a Portal account and the email address must match the email address we have on file for you.

If you do not have access to a Parent/Student Portal account you can request a report card be emailed to you by calling the school your child attends.

Kindergarten report cards will be sent at a later date.

If you need to update your email address or you do not have access to email please contact your school.

post_text:
Meal Delivery Update!
You may pick up meals from 11:00 am- 1:00 p.m. at each elementary school (Monday-Friday).

In addition, buses will run bus routes and deliver meals at regular bus stops. Buses will leave from each elementary school at 7:30 am. You can expect the bus to be at your stop to deliver meals approximately one hour later than regular pick up time in the morning.

Children may receive food once per day at either the school or bus stop. If you arrive in a vehicle, please stay in the vehicle, and we will bring the meal to you. Children must be present to receive a meal.

The bus will not stop at regular stops along highways 5, 515, 60, or Spur 60. Refer to the graphic for more specifics.

Monday's meal will have a peanut product, please contact the nutrition office for an alternative meal at 706- 258-2619.

To limit the spread of COVID-19 and protect the public, the Division of Family and Children Services (DFCS) encourages families to access self-service options online during this period.

Self-service options include:
Apply for Food Stamp and Medicaid Benefits
Visit: gateway.ga.gov (verification documents can also be uploaded and case status info is available for all benefits)
Download an Application:
https://dfcs.georgia.gov/services
Electronic Benefits Transfer (EBT)
Visit: https://www.connectebt.com/gaebtclient or call: 888-421-3281 for updates

Those without internet access can contact the DFCS Customer Contact Center at 877-423-4746 for additional information or to request a paper application. Once completed, applications and any required verification can be mailed back to your local county DFCS office. County office locations are available online at https://dfcs.georgia.gov/locations.

We are working on developing a plan that will allow us to deliver meals to students beginning Wednesday, March 18th. Individual schools will be contacting families concerning online learning and learning packet expectations on Monday.

post_text: Assistant Principal Gini Bell was awarded the Philip Wright Award for lifetime work that benefits students with special needs. She began her career as a special education teacher and carried that knowledge and compassion into her job as an administrator. She has been instrumental in expanding the Special Olympics Program in Fannin. She also serves as a Board Member and Art Gallery Director for the North Georgia Autism Foundation. Pictured (L-R): Mr. Philip Wright, Gini Bell, Shannon Miller, Tracey Pendley (Georgia Teacher of the Year), Dr. Michael Gwatney, and Robert Ensley. We are proud of you Gini!

post_text: Members of the Fannin County Board of Education and leaders from the school district attended a Legislative Site Visit today in Atlanta. They met with leaders of the Georgia School Boards Association and the Georgia School Superintendents Association. They were recognized in the House of Representatives by Speaker David Ralston, and they met with Senator Steve Gooch. Pictures L-R are Director of Achievement Sarah Rigdon, Superintendent Michael Gwatney, Assistant Superintendent Robert Ensley, Board Vice-Chair Terry Bramlett, Board Chair Chad Galloway, and Board Members Mike Cole, Lewis DeWeese, and Bobby Bearden.

There is still uncertainty related to the current weather situation; however, the most recent information from the National Weather Service indicates winter precipitation will arrive in our area around midday. The safety of our students and staff is always the top concern; therefore, Fannin County Schools will be closed today (Friday), February 28. All 12-month personnel should report to work at normal time. All other personnel and students will use COLD today.

Today will be our first COLD day, so 6-12 teachers need to post their first lesson plan by 9:00 a.m.

P-5 students, work on Day 1 of your COLD day packet!

All teachers should conduct office hours via email from 10:00-12:00.

post_text:
If you are tired of being stuck at home, three special events are occurring this evening!
1. At 3:30, the Blue Ridge Mountains Art Association will still host its reception to kick off Youth Art Month, recognizing a number of our young artists from across the system.
2. The Band Concert at FCHS will continue as planned at 7:00 pm. Only HS students will perform.
3. At 6:30, the Swan Drive-in will host Spiderman: Into the Spiderverse, rated PG. This film does include some strobe light effects, so please be aware if you are sensitive to those. The first children who arrive will receive a free book (until supplies run out)! Tickets are $5 per person, and children 5 and under are free. Ticket proceeds will benefit future literacy programming for Fannin’s kids.

More information will be forthcoming about the status of the literacy festival originally planned for the FCHS campus today.

Stay safe and warm, and please join us tonight for a “marvelous” time at one of these events.

post_text:
Exciting News!
In an effort to avoid losing additional instructional time, we are launching a new program that allows students to complete work at home; implementation of this program will allow the day to count toward days attended. This program is called “COLD,” Curriculum Online Learning Day. We will not begin the COLD program until the 5th missed day of school. As of today we have missed 3 days. A call will be sent out from each school this evening with more detailed information and you can visit our website linked below.
We certainly hope we do not miss more days, but it is winter in the North GA Mountains!

The Fannin County School System will operate on a two-hour delay tomorrow (Tuesday) morning, February 11.
Please plan for a two-hour delayed start of school Tuesday morning. This includes all bus routes, as well as the times that parents may drop off children at school on Tuesday morning. Also, be advised that breakfast will not be served, and the schools will dismiss at regular time on Tuesday afternoon.
All principals and 12-month personnel should report to work as close to normal time as safely possible on Tuesday. Any concerns should be reported to your administrator.
If conditions Tuesday morning require a cancellation, this information will be updated.

post_text:
Did you know that the data from the census every 10 years decides funding for:
• Your Title I allocations?
• Head Start dollars?
• School Nutrition support?
• Special Education services?
• Healthcare support?
Did you know that Georgia misses out on millions because it is in the bottom half of "counting rates" in the nation (31st in 2010)?

This means that if we do a better job of making sure that EVERY GEORGIAN IS COUNTED, our communities will receive more federal funding to serve our people!

post_text: Congratulations to BRES, EFES, WFES, and FCMS for obtaining operational status in the statewide Positive Behavior Interventions and Supports Program. In order to earn operational status a school must have a declining discipline trend, have more than 85% of the students with one or less office discipline referral and be implementing the program with fidelity. Way to go!

shared_text:
Fannin County High School
November 5, 2019 at 2:44 PM ·

All veterans of the community are invited to attend Fannin County High School’s annual Veterans Day Recognition program this Wednesday, November 6 in the Performing Arts Center. The program will start at 9:00 a.m and will last approximately one hour. Veterans are asked to arrive at 8:45 a.m. to check in. The program provides students and staff the opportunity to recognize and thank area veterans for their service to our country. Following the program, all veterans are invited to attend a reception in the chorus suite. If you have any questions, please contact the school.
